"At first glance looked like a decent beer. It smelled pretty good, can definitely tell there is cinnamon. That's all I can say is good about this. Personally the cinnamon was overpowering and I was not digging the rice. I tried drinking as much as I could hoping it would get better, but in the end it was a sink poor for me."
"I twisted off the cap and gave it an aggro pour until the foaming action was too much to handle. Backing off, I watched as it formed two fluffy fingers of snow white head with good retention. Color was a slightly hazy Yellow-Gold (SRM = 4 -5 ), but the purity was too flawed for my gold-digging buddies, Midas, Croesus and Mammon to want to show up. Nose smelled like rice pudding with cinnamon atop! I have not had MexiCAN horchata in many years, but this was really evocative of it. Mouthfeel was thin-to-medium. Taste was rice pudding with cinnamon, but not as pronounced as on the nose. That said, as it warmed, it really began to live up to its billing! This was such a pleasant counterbalance to the previous beers this afternoon that I was ecstatic that I had saved it until now. Finish was semi-sweet, but nowhere near as cloying as it could/might have been. I must get #TheOldLady to try some and give me her opinion."
"So this beer is like eating a churro.  Very smooth and the cinnamon is not over powering as I expected.  Body hits heavy but finishes light...whatever that means.  Not what I expected from Coors/Blue Moon but I like this one.  Would seek out if it ever made it to sixers."
